{"key":"post-8752041","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8752041</id>\n<content>Actually, most growers here have hydrotron left over from other projects.&amp;nbsp; They don't replace perlite unless you want to pile them extremely deep.&amp;nbsp; They simply don't have the surface area to evaporate water that perlite has.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I have three bags of hydrotron balls in my garage now.&amp;nbsp; I've tried them with and without standing water and bubblers, and they're simply not worth the trouble.&amp;nbsp; They're intended to provide stability to root systems, not to evaporate water off their surface.&amp;nbsp; Rocks also won't help much.&amp;nbsp; You want the extremely high surface area that perlite has, so once wet, it has a large area to evaporate water from.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8757188</next>\n<prev>8751662</prev>\n<first>8750832</first>\n<last>8757188</last>\n<when>1218377329</when>\n<utime>08/10/08 05:08 PM</utime>\n</post>"}